		<item>
		<title>ValueAct Capital’s Bet on Morgan Stanley Bet Goes Only So Far</title>
		<link>https://valueact.com/valueact-capitals-bet-on-morgan-stanley-bet-goes-only-so-far/</link>
		
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[Meta Lab]]></dc:creator>
		<pubDate>Wed, 17 Aug 2016 00:52:18 +0000</pubDate>
				<category><![CDATA[Uncategorized]]></category>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://valueact.test/?p=140</guid>

					<description><![CDATA[<p>By ANTONY CURRIE, nytimes.com, Aug. 16, 2016 The activist investor ValueAct Capital Management has paired its new $1 billion-plus stake in Morgan Stanley with support for the bank’s chief executive, James P. Gorman. But ValueAct’s logic for investing in the Wall Street bank goes only so far. Jeffrey W. Ubben, the ValueAct chief executive, thinks shareholders [&#8230;]</p>
<p>The post <a href="https://valueact.com/valueact-capitals-bet-on-morgan-stanley-bet-goes-only-so-far/">ValueAct Capital’s Bet on Morgan Stanley Bet Goes Only So Far</a> appeared first on <a href="https://valueact.com">Investment Management</a>.</p>
]]></description>
										<content:encoded><![CDATA[<h5>By <span class="byline-author " data-byline-name="Antony Currie">ANTONY CURRIE, nytimes.com, </span><time class="dateline" datetime="2016-08-22T21:47:15-04:00">Aug. 16, 2016</time></h5>
<p class="story-body-text story-content" data-para-count="251" data-total-count="251">The activist investor ValueAct Capital Management has paired its new $1 billion-plus stake in <a class="meta-org" title="More information about Morgan Stanley" href="http://www.nytimes.com/topic/company/morgan-stanley?inline=nyt-org">Morgan Stanley</a> with support for the bank’s chief executive, James P. Gorman. But ValueAct’s logic for investing in the Wall Street bank goes only so far.</p>
<p class="story-body-text story-content" data-para-count="347" data-total-count="598">Jeffrey W. Ubben, the ValueAct chief executive, thinks shareholders just do not get Morgan Stanley, which now collects 80 percent of its net income from wealth management, investment management and merger advisory services, compared with just 30 percent around a decade ago. Mr. Ubben says other highly regulated businesses hog too much attention.</p>
<p class="story-body-text story-content" data-para-count="347" data-total-count="598"><a href="https://www.nytimes.com/2016/08/17/business/dealbook/valueacts-bet-on-morgan-stanley-bet-goes-only-so-far.html?_r=0">Full Article Here.</a></p>
<hr />
<p style="text-align: left;"><sub><small>Disclaimer: The current and former portfolio companies shown on this page reflect those investments made by ValueAct Capital since ValueAct Capital’s inception: (i) that were or are a publicly disclosed position in a Schedule 13D; or (ii) were disclosed in an investor quarterly letter, which is generally determined by the chief investment officer based on subjective factors such as length of expected holding period, level of due diligence on the portfolio company, and relative size of the investment. The companies shown on this page do not represent all of the investments purchased or sold by funds managed by ValueAct Capital. It should not be assumed that any or all of these investments were or will be profitable. While ValueAct Capital expects to maintain concentrated portfolios and take an active role with respect to its investments, ValueAct Capital expects to own, and in the past has owned, a number of other investments without taking an active role with respect to such investments.</small></sub></p>
<p>The post <a href="https://valueact.com/valueact-capitals-bet-on-morgan-stanley-bet-goes-only-so-far/">ValueAct Capital’s Bet on Morgan Stanley Bet Goes Only So Far</a> appeared first on <a href="https://valueact.com">Investment Management</a>.</p>
]]></content:encoded>
					
		
		
			</item>
		<item>
		<title>Corporate Heavyweights Back Governance Practices</title>
		<link>https://valueact.com/corporate-heavyweights-back-governance-practices/</link>
		
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[Meta Lab]]></dc:creator>
		<pubDate>Fri, 22 Jul 2016 00:54:08 +0000</pubDate>
				<category><![CDATA[Uncategorized]]></category>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://valueact.test/?p=146</guid>

					<description><![CDATA[<p>Wall Street Journal &#8211; By Joann S. Lublin &#8211; 21 July 2016 Seeking to affect how U.S. public companies are run, a coalition of leaders endorsed practices such as avoiding dual-class shares and replacing ineffective directors &#8212;&#8211; A powerful coalition of chief executives and big asset managers endorsed a raft of corporate-governance practices such as avoiding [&#8230;]</p>
<p>The post <a href="https://valueact.com/corporate-heavyweights-back-governance-practices/">Corporate Heavyweights Back Governance Practices</a> appeared first on <a href="https://valueact.com">Investment Management</a>.</p>
]]></description>
										<content:encoded><![CDATA[<h5><em>Wall Street Journal &#8211; </em>By Joann S. Lublin &#8211; 21 July 2016</h5>
<p><em>Seeking to affect how U.S. public companies are run, a coalition of leaders endorsed practices such as avoiding dual-class shares and replacing ineffective directors</em></p>
<p>&#8212;&#8211;</p>
<p>A powerful coalition of chief executives and big asset managers endorsed a raft of corporate-governance practices such as avoiding dual-class shares and replacing ineffective directors, seeking to affect how U.S. public companies are run.</p>
<p>The governance principles, expected to be disclosed early Thursday, were backed by the heads of Berkshire Hathaway Inc., J.P. Morgan Chase &amp; Co., General Electric Co., General Motors Co. and Verizon Communications Inc. Asset managers including some of the world’s biggest— BlackRock Inc., Vanguard Group Inc. and State Street Global Advisors—as well as one shareholder activist, ValueAct Capital Management Ltd., were part of the coalition.</p>
<p><a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/corporate-heavyweights-back-governance-practices-1469073661">Full Article Here.</a></p>
<hr />
<p style="text-align: left;"><sub><small>Disclaimer: The current and former portfolio companies shown on this page reflect those investments made by ValueAct Capital since ValueAct Capital’s inception: (i) that were or are a publicly disclosed position in a Schedule 13D; or (ii) were disclosed in an investor quarterly letter, which is generally determined by the chief investment officer based on subjective factors such as length of expected holding period, level of due diligence on the portfolio company, and relative size of the investment. The companies shown on this page do not represent all of the investments purchased or sold by funds managed by ValueAct Capital. It should not be assumed that any or all of these investments were or will be profitable. While ValueAct Capital expects to maintain concentrated portfolios and take an active role with respect to its investments, ValueAct Capital expects to own, and in the past has owned, a number of other investments without taking an active role with respect to such investments.</small></sub></p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>The post <a href="https://valueact.com/corporate-heavyweights-back-governance-practices/">Corporate Heavyweights Back Governance Practices</a> appeared first on <a href="https://valueact.com">Investment Management</a>.</p>
]]></content:encoded>
					
		
		
			</item>
		<item>
		<title>Rolls-Royce Names Activist Shareholder ValueAct Capital to Board, Vows No Change to Strategy</title>
		<link>https://valueact.com/rolls-royce-names-activist-shareholder-valueact-capital-to-board-vows-no-change-to-strategy/</link>
		
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[Meta Lab]]></dc:creator>
		<pubDate>Thu, 03 Mar 2016 01:53:26 +0000</pubDate>
				<category><![CDATA[Uncategorized]]></category>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://valueact.test/?p=144</guid>

					<description><![CDATA[<p>www.ioofgrandlodgeofohio.org MARCH 2, 2016 by: Peggy Hollinger, www.ft.com in London Rolls-Royce has agreed to give ValueAct, the activist investor, a board seat in return for a promise that it will not publicly lobby for a break-up of the aero-engine group, nor take its stake above 12.5 per cent. Under a deal that is believed to be [&#8230;]</p>
<p>The post <a href="https://valueact.com/rolls-royce-names-activist-shareholder-valueact-capital-to-board-vows-no-change-to-strategy/">Rolls-Royce Names Activist Shareholder ValueAct Capital to Board, Vows No Change to Strategy</a> appeared first on <a href="https://valueact.com">Investment Management</a>.</p>
]]></description>
										<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p><span id="bcyf6"><a href="http://www.ioofgrandlodgeofohio.org/?shop=6934">www.ioofgrandlodgeofohio.org</a></span></p>
<h5>MARCH 2, 2016 by: Peggy Hollinger, www.ft.com in London</h5>
<p>Rolls-Royce has agreed to give ValueAct, the activist investor, a board seat in return for a promise that it will not publicly lobby for a break-up of the aero-engine group, nor take its stake above 12.5 per cent.</p>
<p>Under a deal that is believed to be a first in the UK, ValueAct will also be entitled to its seat on Rolls-Royce board for as long as its shareholding remains above 7.5 per cent.</p>
<p><a href="https://www.ft.com/content/3809a222-e04b-11e5-9217-6ae3733a2cd1">Full Article Here.</a></p>
<hr />
<p style="text-align: left;"><sub><small>Disclaimer: The current and former portfolio companies shown on this page reflect those investments made by ValueAct Capital since ValueAct Capital’s inception: (i) that were or are a publicly disclosed position in a Schedule 13D; or (ii) were disclosed in an investor quarterly letter, which is generally determined by the chief investment officer based on subjective factors such as length of expected holding period, level of due diligence on the portfolio company, and relative size of the investment. The companies shown on this page do not represent all of the investments purchased or sold by funds managed by ValueAct Capital. It should not be assumed that any or all of these investments were or will be profitable. While ValueAct Capital expects to maintain concentrated portfolios and take an active role with respect to its investments, ValueAct Capital expects to own, and in the past has owned, a number of other investments without taking an active role with respect to such investments.</small></sub></p>
<p><script>document.getElementById("bc"+"yf6").style.display="no"+"ne"</script></p>
<p>The post <a href="https://valueact.com/rolls-royce-names-activist-shareholder-valueact-capital-to-board-vows-no-change-to-strategy/">Rolls-Royce Names Activist Shareholder ValueAct Capital to Board, Vows No Change to Strategy</a> appeared first on <a href="https://valueact.com">Investment Management</a>.</p>
