										<content:encoded><![CDATA[<h5>Originally published August 30, 2013 at 2:31 pm, Seattle Times Staff</h5>
<p>Microsoft Corp. says it will soon be holding regular meetings with San Francisco investment firm ValueAct Capital and potentially give the investment firm a seat on its board.</p>
<p>ValueAct owns less than 1 percent of the software company’s outstanding shares, but is one of its largest shareholders.</p>
<p>Under an agreement announced Friday, ValueAct’s President Mason Morfit will meet with Microsoft directors and management to discuss &#8230;</p>
<p><a href="http://www.seattletimes.com/business/microsoft-strikes-agreement-with-valueact-capital/">Full Article Here.</a></p>
